<subSubSection pageNumber="863" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="863">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="863">Note:</emphasis>
Gray (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="863">Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts</emphasis>
17: 178. 1882), in a study of the 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Solidago" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="863">Solidago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
material in the Linnaean herbarium, believed there to be no relevant specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Solidago" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caesia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="863">S. caesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, concluding that the name is &quot;founded on&quot; the cited Dillenian illustration and associated material in OXF. Taylor &amp; Taylor (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="863">Sida</emphasis>
10: 228. 1984) indicated both this plate and 998.14 (LINN) as 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“type”">&quot;type&quot;</normalizedToken>
, and Uttal (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="863">Sida</emphasis>
10: 324. 1984) appears to have been the first to formalise a choice. Reveal &amp; al. (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="863">Huntia</emphasis>
7: 238. 1987) provide a concise summary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
